  "raw_response": "{\n  \"title\": \"COVID Crash example distinguishing true vs. failed moving average breakouts using momentum, candle close, and confirmation\",\n  \"school\": \"Indicator-Based\",\n  \"asset\": null,\n  \"timeframe\": null,\n  \"market_context\": \"The case analyzes the stock market crash during the early COVID-19 pandemic, using it as a real-world example to illustrate how to differentiate valid moving average breakouts from false ones.\",\n  \"key_observation\": \"True breakouts occur with strong momentum candles, decisive closes far below/above the MA, high volume, and price action confirmation; failed breakouts show shallow dips and weak closes near the MA.\",\n  \"analysis_steps\": [\n    \"Step 1: Identify clear breakouts (price decisively crossing below/above the moving average) versus failed breakouts (brief dips followed by reversal).\",\n    \"Step 2: Assess momentum by comparing candle real body size—true breakouts feature candles at least 2–4x larger than preceding candles.\",\n    \"Step 3: Evaluate candle close relative to the moving average—strong breakouts have closes far below (downtrend) or above (uptrend) the MA, not near it.\",\n    \"Step 4: Consider volume as confirmation—higher volume during the breakout increases its significance (though volume indicator not shown on chart).\",\n    \"Step 5: Look for price action confirmation—e.g., a second candle closing beyond the MA, or a break of prior market structure (e.g., swing low), or retest of former support as resistance.\"\n  ],\n  \"outcome\": null,\n ",
